<subSubSection id="88916555ED4C7D68B764F443C82B7CCE" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C03436DEED4C7D68B764F443C82B7CCE" blockId="17.[803,1398,2772,3200]" lastBlockId="17.[189,1396,3207,3477]" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">
Morphologically and genetically, J. orienta lis is a member of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="078B4D5DED4C7D68B0B7F41CCE477BD4" authorityName="Brandt" authorityYear="1844" box="[1270,1390,3009,3042]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Haltomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Haltomys</taxonomicName>
, the sister group of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="078B4D5DED4C7D68B14BF435CE477C3F" authorityName="Erxleben" authorityYear="1777" box="[1290,1390,3048,3081]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Jaculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Jaculus</taxonomicName>
. Molecular reconstructions retrieved two divergent allopatric lineages in North Africa: one in Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, and western Libya and another in eastern Libya and Egypt. These two lineages diverged c.0-67 million years ago. Sinai Peninsula and Israel populations have not been studied genetically. Three subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
